<p>
  every year, around the last week of june and the first two weeks of july, something predictable happens. millions of uk households open their bank statements — or their emails — and discover that something quietly renewed without their knowledge.
</p>

<h3>the july renewal cluster</h3>

<p>
  there's a reason july is so concentrated. many policies are structured to begin at the start of a new financial quarter. car insurance retailers price on 12-month cycles, which for the uk means a huge number of policies initiated in july 2025 are now hitting renewal. home insurance follows the same pattern. even broadband contracts — typically 18 or 24 months — see an unusual spike of completions landing in the july window.
</p>

<p>
  gym memberships are another july offender. the post-holiday "get fit for summer" push in january creates a delayed wave of minimum-term completions. people who signed up in january 2025 on a 12-month minimum term are now free to leave — but their gym banked on them forgetting.
</p>

<h3>what's happening in july 2026</h3>

<p>
  this year is particularly acute. the fca's consumer duty rules, phased in through 2024 and 2025, require firms to give clearer renewal communications and fair value assessments. but the data shows the practice hasn't changed as much as the language. providers use compliant wording while still silently hiking prices on loyal customers.
</p>

<p>
  the average car insurance renewal premium in the uk is now approximately £540, up 20% year-on-year according to the association of british insurers. but here's the split that matters: <strong>new customers pay around £420. existing customers who don't switch pay £540.</strong> that £120 gap is the loyalty penalty in action, and july is the month it hits most aggressively.
</p>

<h3>what you should watch for this month</h3>

<p>
  if you haven't checked your renewals this month, here's a quick audit for the next 10 minutes:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>car insurance.</strong> did you auto-renew last year? check your provider's quote against at least two comparison sites. the difference is rarely under £40.</li>
  <li><strong>broadband.</strong> when did your contract end? if you're past the minimum term, your monthly price is almost certainly £10–15 higher than it should be.</li>
  <li><strong>gym memberships.</strong> did you join in january? your 12-month minimum is up. if you're going, negotiate. if you're not, cancel.</li>
  <li><strong>subscription renewals.</strong> streaming services, cloud storage, software subscriptions — many of these land on annual cycles that were initiated mid-2025.</li>
</ul>

